@namespace Lumeo
@using System.ComponentModel
@using System.Globalization
@using Lumeo.GanttV3
@attribute [EditorBrowsable(EditorBrowsableState.Never)]

@* Gantt3 — v3's root component (design spec Phase 2, T2 "read-only markup";
   working name — renamed in Phase 4 once it replaces the v2 Gantt public API).
   Owns a GanttState instance and renders GanttNav + GanttTimeline against it.
   No drag/resize/progress editing and no JS interop here — that is later
   phases; this is a pure, static read model of GanttScale + GanttState.
   The tree pane (T3) is deliberately NOT built here.

   NOTE (accessibility): see GanttBar.razor's NOTE — the Razor compiler always
   generates a component's class as `public`, so despite the task spec asking
   for `internal`, this stays `public` and its new members are recorded in
   PublicAPI.Unshipped.txt; flagged for the reviewer/team lead to confirm.
   [EditorBrowsable(Never)] keeps this working-name API out of consumer
   IntelliSense until the Phase-4 rename (fix-round follow-up). *@
<div class="@RootClass" @attributes="AdditionalAttributes">
    <GanttNav ViewMode="@_state.ViewMode"
              ViewModeChanged="HandleViewModeChangedAsync"
              PeriodLabel="@PeriodLabel"
              OnToday="GoToTodayAsync"
              OnPrevious="ShiftToPreviousAsync"
              OnNext="ShiftToNextAsync" />

    @* Phase 2's "one shared scroll container wrapping both panes" (T3 design
       spec, scroll sync): tree pane + timeline are laid out side by side as
       plain flex siblings INSIDE this single overflow:auto div, so vertical
       scrolling moves both together with no JS scroll-sync needed yet — the
       timeline keeps its own nested horizontal scroll (GanttTimeline.RootClass)
       for its much-wider canvas, which the tree pane never needs. *@
    <div class="rounded-md border border-border/60" style="max-height:@Height;overflow:auto;">
        @* Rows is a computed property (see below) — read it into a local ONCE
           per render and hand the same value to both bindings below, rather
           than letting each binding re-invoke the property (which would run
           GanttRowModel.BuildVisibleRows twice per render for no reason). *@
        @{ var rows = Rows; }
        <div class="flex">
            @if (EffectiveShowTreePane)
            {
                <GanttTree Rows="@rows" OnToggleCollapse="HandleToggleCollapseAsync" />
            }
            <GanttTimeline Tasks="@_state.Tasks"
                           Rows="@rows"
                           ViewMode="@_state.ViewMode"
                           RangeStart="@_state.VisibleRange.Start"
                           RangeEnd="@_state.VisibleRange.End"
                           BarHeight="@BarHeight"
                           ColumnWidth="@ColumnWidth"
                           TodayHighlight="@TodayHighlight"
                           BarColor="@BarColor"
                           BarTemplate="@BarTemplate"
                           Class="min-w-0 flex-1" />
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

@code {
    /// <summary>The tasks (and milestones) rendered as bars.</summary>
    [Parameter] public IEnumerable<GanttTask>? Tasks { get; set; }

    /// <summary>The active zoom level. Two-way bindable via <see cref="ViewModeChanged"/>. Default <see cref="GanttViewMode.Day"/>.</summary>
    [Parameter] public GanttViewMode ViewMode { get; set; } = GanttViewMode.Day;

    /// <summary>Raised when the user picks a new zoom level from <see cref="GanttNav"/>'s toolbar.</summary>
    [Parameter] public EventCallback<GanttViewMode> ViewModeChanged { get; set; }

    /// <summary>CSS max-height of the timeline's scrollable viewport. Default <c>"500px"</c>.</summary>
    [Parameter] public string Height { get; set; } = "500px";

    /// <summary>Highlight today with a vertical marker line. Default true.</summary>
    [Parameter] public bool TodayHighlight { get; set; } = true;

    /// <summary>Override the pixel height of each task bar (default <see cref="GanttScale.DefaultBarHeight"/>).</summary>
    [Parameter] public int? BarHeight { get; set; }

    /// <summary>Override the pixel width of each date column for the current view mode.</summary>
    [Parameter] public int? ColumnWidth { get; set; }

    /// <summary>Per-task bar colour override — same contract as v2's <c>Gantt.BarColor</c>.</summary>
    [Parameter] public Func<GanttTask, string?>? BarColor { get; set; }

    /// <summary>
    /// Optional grouping function. When set, tasks are sorted by group label
    /// (stable within a group) before rendering — mirrors v2's GroupBy sort.
    /// Visual group-header rows are a tree-pane (T3) concern, not built here.
    /// </summary>
    [Parameter] public Func<GanttTask, string>? GroupBy { get; set; }

    /// <summary>Replaces a bar's default label content when set.</summary>
    [Parameter] public RenderFragment<GanttTask>? BarTemplate { get; set; }

    /// <summary>
    /// Shows the left tree/list pane (design spec Phase 2, T3). Null (the
    /// default) resolves to <see cref="GanttRowModel.DefaultShowTreePane"/>: on
    /// when <see cref="GroupBy"/> is set or any task sets
    /// <see cref="GanttTask.ParentId"/>, off otherwise — a flat task list with
    /// neither gets the same single-pane layout T2 always rendered.
    /// </summary>
    [Parameter] public bool? ShowTreePane { get; set; }

    /// <summary>Additional CSS classes merged onto the root element.</summary>
    [Parameter] public string? Class { get; set; }

    /// <summary>Captures unmatched attributes and applies them to the root element.</summary>
    [Parameter(CaptureUnmatchedValues = true)] public Dictionary<string, object>? AdditionalAttributes { get; set; }

    // Owned outright for now (design spec "keep it simple: internal field for
    // now") — Phase 3 promotes this to a hoistable `State` parameter so a
    // separately rendered GanttNav/GanttTimeline pair can share one instance
    // without either owning the other's lifetime (see GanttState's remarks).
    private readonly GanttState _state = new();

    private string RootClass => Cx.Merge("flex flex-col gap-3", Class);

    // The single, shared row list GanttTree/GanttTimeline/GanttArrowLayer all
    // render against (design spec Phase 2, T3 — see GanttRowModel's remarks).
    // Recomputed fresh from _state each render; cheap (a linear pass over the
    // task list) and always in lockstep with _state.Tasks/_state.Collapsed.
    private IReadOnlyList<GanttVisibleRow> Rows => GanttRowModel.BuildVisibleRows(_state.Tasks, _state.Collapsed);

    private bool EffectiveShowTreePane => ShowTreePane ?? GanttRowModel.DefaultShowTreePane(_state.Tasks, GroupBy is not null);

    private Task HandleToggleCollapseAsync(string key)
    {
        _state.ToggleCollapsed(key);
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    }

    // Controlled/uncontrolled ViewMode discriminators — same pattern as v2's
    // Gantt.razor (_lastSeenViewMode/_lastPushedViewMode), trimmed to what a
    // read-only tree needs: no drag/refresh interop to reconcile against.
    private GanttViewMode _lastSeenViewMode;
    private GanttViewMode _lastPushedViewMode;
    private bool _rangeInitialized;

    protected override void OnInitialized()
    {
        _lastSeenViewMode = ViewMode;
        _lastPushedViewMode = ViewMode;
        _state.SetViewMode(ViewMode);
        _state.SetTasks(SortedTasks(Tasks?.ToList() ?? new List<GanttTask>()));
        _state.SetVisibleRange(ComputeInitialRange(_state.ViewMode, _state.Tasks));
        _rangeInitialized = true;
    }

    protected override void OnParametersSet()
    {
        _state.SetTasks(SortedTasks(Tasks?.ToList() ?? new List<GanttTask>()));

        // CONTROLLED (ViewModeChanged bound): adopt ViewMode whenever it differs
        // from what we last pushed — an echo of our own push is a no-op.
        // UNCONTROLLED: only a genuine change against the last SEEN parameter
        // value is authoritative, so an unrelated parent re-render doesn't
        // silently revert a toolbar zoom the user just picked.
        var viewModeChanged = ViewModeChanged.HasDelegate
            ? ViewMode != _lastPushedViewMode
            : ViewMode != _lastSeenViewMode;
        _lastSeenViewMode = ViewMode;

        if (viewModeChanged || !_rangeInitialized)
        {
            _lastPushedViewMode = ViewMode;
            _state.SetViewMode(ViewMode);
            _state.SetVisibleRange(ComputeInitialRange(_state.ViewMode, _state.Tasks));
            _rangeInitialized = true;
        }
    }

    private List<GanttTask> SortedTasks(List<GanttTask> raw)
    {
        if (GroupBy is null) return raw;
        return raw
            .Select((t, i) => (t, i))
            .OrderBy(x => GroupBy(x.t))
            .ThenBy(x => x.i)
            .Select(x => x.t)
            .ToList();
    }

    // Faithful port of gantt-v2.js's render() min/max + per-unit padding preamble
    // (gantt-v2.js lines 155-190) — GanttScale.BuildDateUnits deliberately leaves
    // this to its caller (see its own remarks), and this is that caller.
    private static GanttDateRange ComputeInitialRange(GanttViewMode mode, IReadOnlyList<GanttTask> tasks)
    {
        DateTime minDate, maxDate;
        if (tasks.Count > 0)
        {
            minDate = tasks.Min(t => t.Start);
            maxDate = tasks.Max(t => t.IsMilestone ? t.Start : t.End);
        }
        else
        {
            var today = DateTime.Today;
            minDate = today.AddDays(-7);
            maxDate = today.AddDays(14);
        }

        var cfg = GanttScale.GetConfig(mode);
        return cfg.Unit switch
        {
            GanttScaleUnit.Day => new GanttDateRange(
                minDate.AddDays(-cfg.PadBefore * cfg.Step),
                maxDate.AddDays(cfg.PadAfter * cfg.Step)),
            GanttScaleUnit.Month => new GanttDateRange(
                new DateTime(minDate.Year, minDate.Month, 1, 0, 0, 0, minDate.Kind).AddMonths(-cfg.PadBefore),
                new DateTime(maxDate.Year, maxDate.Month, 1, 0, 0, 0, maxDate.Kind).AddMonths(cfg.PadAfter)),
            GanttScaleUnit.Year => new GanttDateRange(
                new DateTime(minDate.Year - cfg.PadBefore, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, minDate.Kind),
                new DateTime(maxDate.Year + cfg.PadAfter, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, maxDate.Kind)),
            GanttScaleUnit.Hour => new GanttDateRange(
                minDate.AddDays(-Math.Ceiling(cfg.PadBefore * cfg.Step / 24.0)),
                maxDate.AddDays(Math.Ceiling(cfg.PadAfter * cfg.Step / 24.0))),
            _ => new GanttDateRange(minDate, maxDate),
        };
    }

    private string PeriodLabel
    {
        get
        {
            var range = _state.VisibleRange;
            return _state.ViewMode switch
            {
                GanttViewMode.Year => $"{range.Start.Year}–{range.End.Year}",
                GanttViewMode.Month => range.Start.ToString("MMMM yyyy", CultureInfo.CurrentCulture),
                _ => $"{range.Start.ToString("MMM d, yyyy", CultureInfo.CurrentCulture)} – {range.End.ToString("MMM d, yyyy", CultureInfo.CurrentCulture)}",
            };
        }
    }

    private async Task HandleViewModeChangedAsync(GanttViewMode mode)
    {
        if (mode == _state.ViewMode) return;
        _lastPushedViewMode = mode;
        _state.SetViewMode(mode);
        _state.SetVisibleRange(ComputeInitialRange(mode, _state.Tasks));
        if (ViewModeChanged.HasDelegate) await ViewModeChanged.InvokeAsync(mode);
        else ViewMode = mode; // uncontrolled: keep our own field in lock-step for the next OnParametersSet comparison
    }

    // "Shift VisibleRange by the mode's step" — literally GanttScaleConfig.Step
    // in GanttScaleConfig.Unit, applied to both ends of the window so its
    // duration is preserved (a single page forward/back, not a resize).
    private Task ShiftAsync(int direction)
    {
        var cfg = GanttScale.GetConfig(_state.ViewMode);
        var range = _state.VisibleRange;
        var amount = direction * cfg.Step;
        var (start, end) = cfg.Unit switch
        {
            GanttScaleUnit.Day => (range.Start.AddDays(amount), range.End.AddDays(amount)),
            GanttScaleUnit.Month => (range.Start.AddMonths(amount), range.End.AddMonths(amount)),
            GanttScaleUnit.Year => (range.Start.AddYears(amount), range.End.AddYears(amount)),
            GanttScaleUnit.Hour => (range.Start.AddHours(amount), range.End.AddHours(amount)),
            _ => (range.Start, range.End),
        };
        _state.SetVisibleRange(start, end);
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    }

    private Task ShiftToPreviousAsync() => ShiftAsync(-1);
    private Task ShiftToNextAsync() => ShiftAsync(1);

    // Recenters the CURRENT window (same duration) on today, rather than
    // resetting to the tasks' original padded range.
    private Task GoToTodayAsync()
    {
        var range = _state.VisibleRange;
        var width = range.End - range.Start;
        var today = DateTime.Today;
        var half = new TimeSpan(width.Ticks / 2);
        _state.SetVisibleRange(today - half, today + half);
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    }
}

@namespace Lumeo
@using System.ComponentModel
@using Lumeo.GanttV3
@attribute [EditorBrowsable(EditorBrowsableState.Never)]

@* GanttArrowLayer — SVG overlay drawing one path + arrowhead per dependency
   edge between two currently-visible rows (design spec Phase 2, T3). Absolutely
   positioned over GanttTimeline's canvas at the canvas's own full size,
   pointer-events:none so it never intercepts bar interaction (mirrors v2's own
   arrows, which carry no pointer handlers either — gantt-v2.js lines 660-667).

   Geometry is entirely delegated to GanttScale.BarGeometry (bar left/width) +
   GanttArrowRouting (path/arrowhead math) — this component has no date/pixel
   math of its own, and deliberately recomputes bar geometry independently
   rather than reaching into GanttTimeline's private row state: both consume
   the same Rows list + the same GanttScale helpers, so they can never
   silently disagree without one of the shared pure functions itself being
   wrong (and a wrong shared function would show up as a routing-math test
   failure, not a rendering-layer coupling bug).

   Arrows for a task hidden by a collapsed ancestor/group are simply absent:
   that task never appears in Rows, so it has no entry in the geometry lookup
   below, and any dependency naming it — as either source or target — is
   silently skipped, mirroring v2's own guards (`if (!source) continue;` /
   `if (!target) return;`, gantt-v2.js lines 649-653). *@
<svg class="@RootClass" width="@Width" height="@Height" viewBox="@ViewBox" style="@RootStyle" @attributes="AdditionalAttributes">
    @foreach (var arrow in Arrows)
    {
        <path class="lumeo-gantt-v3-arrow" d="@arrow.PathD" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-muted-foreground)" stroke-width="1.2" opacity="0.6" data-arrow-from="@arrow.FromTaskId" data-arrow-to="@arrow.ToTaskId" />
        <polygon class="lumeo-gantt-v3-arrowhead" points="@arrow.ArrowheadPoints" fill="var(--color-muted-foreground)" opacity="0.6" />
    }
</svg>

@code {
    /// <summary>The currently visible rows — same list GanttTree/GanttTimeline render against, so a collapsed-away task never produces an arrow (see remarks above).</summary>
    [Parameter] public IReadOnlyList<GanttVisibleRow> Rows { get; set; } = Array.Empty<GanttVisibleRow>();

    /// <summary>The active zoom level — feeds <see cref="GanttScale.BarGeometry"/> for each visible task.</summary>
    [Parameter] public GanttViewMode ViewMode { get; set; } = GanttViewMode.Day;

    /// <summary>The timeline's date origin (first rendered column's date) — same value GanttTimeline computes as its own <c>Origin</c>.</summary>
    [Parameter] public DateTime Origin { get; set; }

    /// <summary>The effective column width in pixels — same value GanttTimeline passes as its own <c>EffectiveColumnWidth</c>.</summary>
    [Parameter] public int ColumnWidth { get; set; }

    /// <summary>The effective bar height in pixels — same value GanttTimeline passes as its own <c>EffectiveBarHeight</c>.</summary>
    [Parameter] public int BarHeight { get; set; } = GanttScale.DefaultBarHeight;

    /// <summary>The overlay's pixel width — matches GanttTimeline's canvas <c>TotalWidth</c>.</summary>
    [Parameter] public double Width { get; set; }

    /// <summary>The overlay's pixel height — matches GanttTimeline's canvas <c>CanvasHeight</c>.</summary>
    [Parameter] public double Height { get; set; }

    /// <summary>Additional CSS classes merged onto the root <c>&lt;svg&gt;</c>.</summary>
    [Parameter] public string? Class { get; set; }

    /// <summary>Captures unmatched attributes and applies them to the root <c>&lt;svg&gt;</c>.</summary>
    [Parameter(CaptureUnmatchedValues = true)] public Dictionary<string, object>? AdditionalAttributes { get; set; }

    private string RootClass => Cx.Merge("pointer-events-none absolute inset-0", Class);
    private string ViewBox => FormattableString.Invariant($"0 0 {Width} {Height}");
    private string RootStyle => FormattableString.Invariant($"width:{Width}px;height:{Height}px;");

    /// <summary>One resolved dependency edge ready to render, keyed by the two task ids it connects (for the DOM's <c>data-arrow-from</c>/<c>data-arrow-to</c>, and for test assertions).</summary>
    internal readonly record struct GanttArrowInfo(string FromTaskId, string ToTaskId, string PathD, string ArrowheadPoints);

    private List<GanttArrowInfo> Arrows
    {
        get
        {
            // Same geometry every visible GanttBar occupies — see the type
            // remarks for why this is computed here rather than shared via a
            // cross-component reference.
            var geometryByTaskId = new Dictionary<string, GanttArrowRouting.BarGeometry>();
            for (var i = 0; i < Rows.Count; i++)
            {
                var task = Rows[i].Task;
                if (task is null) continue; // group-header slot — no bar, no geometry
                var (x, width) = GanttScale.BarGeometry(task, ViewMode, Origin, ColumnWidth, BarHeight);
                geometryByTaskId[task.Id] = new GanttArrowRouting.BarGeometry(x, width, i);
            }

            var arrows = new List<GanttArrowInfo>();
            foreach (var row in Rows)
            {
                var task = row.Task;
                if (task?.Dependencies is null || task.Dependencies.Length == 0) continue;
                if (!geometryByTaskId.TryGetValue(task.Id, out var target)) continue;

                foreach (var dependsOnId in task.Dependencies)
                {
                    if (!geometryByTaskId.TryGetValue(dependsOnId, out var source)) continue;
                    var pathD = GanttArrowRouting.ComputePathD(source, target, BarHeight);
                    var arrowheadPoints = GanttArrowRouting.ComputeArrowheadPoints(target, BarHeight);
                    arrows.Add(new GanttArrowInfo(dependsOnId, task.Id, pathD, arrowheadPoints));
                }
            }
            return arrows;
        }
    }
}

namespace Lumeo.GanttV3;

/// <summary>
/// Pure, static dependency-arrow geometry — a faithful 1:1 port of gantt-v2.js's
/// arrow-drawing block (<c>render()</c>'s trailing <c>tasks.forEach</c> loop,
/// gantt-v2.js lines 646-669). Read end-to-end before porting: v2 uses exactly
/// ONE routing formula for every dependency edge — there is no branch for
/// "target left of source", "same row", or any other relative geometry; the
/// elbow path and arrowhead are computed identically regardless of where the
/// target bar sits relative to the source bar. This port is therefore
/// intentionally unconditional too — see <see cref="ComputePathD"/>'s remarks
/// for what that means when the target is behind the source.
/// </summary>
internal static class GanttArrowRouting
{
    /// <summary>
    /// A dependency arrow's endpoint geometry as the router needs it: the bar's
    /// left edge, width, and row slot (row slot recovers the bar's vertical
    /// center via <see cref="GanttScale.BarTop"/> — the same value
    /// <see cref="GanttScale.BarGeometry"/> and a rendered <c>GanttBar</c> use).
    /// </summary>
    internal readonly record struct BarGeometry(double X, double Width, int RowIndex);

    /// <summary>
    /// SVG path <c>d</c> attribute for one dependency arrow from
    /// <paramref name="source"/> (the depended-upon task) to
    /// <paramref name="target"/> (the dependent task). Faithful port of:
    /// <code>
    /// const sx = source.x + source.w;
    /// const sy = source.y + BAR_HEIGHT / 2;
    /// const tx = target.x;
    /// const ty = target.y + BAR_HEIGHT / 2;
    /// const midX = sx + 12;
    /// const path = `M ${sx} ${sy} L ${midX} ${sy} L ${midX} ${ty} L ${tx - 4} ${ty}`;
    /// </code>
    /// (gantt-v2.js lines 654-659). Because v2 has no "target behind source"
    /// branch, a backward dependency (target's left edge is to the LEFT of
    /// <c>midX</c>) still routes through the same forward-projecting elbow —
    /// the path visually loops out to the right of the source bar before
    /// doubling back left to the target, exactly as v2 renders it. Likewise a
    /// same-row dependency (<c>source.RowIndex == target.RowIndex</c>) produces
    /// a path whose two elbow points share the same Y — a redundant-looking but
    /// harmless <c>L</c> segment of zero vertical extent, again matching v2
    /// verbatim rather than special-casing it away.
    /// </summary>
    internal static string ComputePathD(BarGeometry source, BarGeometry target, int barHeight)
    {
        var (sx, sy) = SourceEdge(source, barHeight);
        var (tx, ty) = TargetEdge(target, barHeight);
        var midX = sx + 12;

        return FormattableString.Invariant($"M {sx} {sy} L {midX} {sy} L {midX} {ty} L {tx - 4} {ty}");
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// SVG <c>points</c> attribute for one dependency arrow's arrowhead
    /// triangle, anchored at <paramref name="target"/>'s left edge. Faithful
    /// port of:
    /// <code>
    /// points: `${tx - 6},${ty - 4} ${tx},${ty} ${tx - 6},${ty + 4}`
    /// </code>
    /// (gantt-v2.js line 665).
    /// </summary>
    internal static string ComputeArrowheadPoints(BarGeometry target, int barHeight)
    {
        var (tx, ty) = TargetEdge(target, barHeight);

        return FormattableString.Invariant($"{tx - 6},{ty - 4} {tx},{ty} {tx - 6},{ty + 4}");
    }

    // sx = source.x + source.w; sy = source.y + BAR_HEIGHT / 2 (gantt-v2.js:654-655).
    // "source.y" in v2 is the bar's already-computed top (taskById's stored `y`,
    // itself `barY` — see GanttScale.BarTop's remarks), not the row's raw top.
    //
    // The "+ GanttScale.HeaderHeight" below is NOT part of GanttScale.BarTop
    // itself (adding it there would double-count it for GanttBar, which gets
    // its own HeaderHeight offset for free via DOM nesting — see BarTop's own
    // remarks: "the row CANVAS's own top offset, added by the caller"). A
    // rendered GanttBar sits inside GanttTimeline's row-canvas div, which
    // starts HeaderHeight px below the outer canvas div's top purely because
    // the header div renders BEFORE it in normal document flow. GanttArrowLayer's
    // <svg>, however, is "absolute inset-0" against that SAME OUTER canvas div
    // (not the row-canvas div) — see GanttArrowLayer.razor's RootClass — so its
    // own coordinate origin is the top of the HEADER, not the top of the rows.
    // Without this offset every arrow rendered ~HeaderHeight px (56px) too high,
    // floating near the header instead of touching the bars it connects
    // (parity-harness finding, feat/gantt-v3 T4: v2's flat single-SVG canvas has
    // no such split coordinate space, so its own barY already includes
    // HEADER_HEIGHT — gantt-v2.js line 454 — and never had this bug).
    private static (double X, double Y) SourceEdge(BarGeometry source, int barHeight)
    {
        var sy = GanttScale.HeaderHeight + GanttScale.BarTop(source.RowIndex, barHeight) + barHeight / 2.0;
        return (source.X + source.Width, sy);
    }

    // tx = target.x; ty = target.y + BAR_HEIGHT / 2 (gantt-v2.js:656-657).
    private static (double X, double Y) TargetEdge(BarGeometry target, int barHeight)
    {
        var ty = GanttScale.HeaderHeight + GanttScale.BarTop(target.RowIndex, barHeight) + barHeight / 2.0;
        return (target.X, ty);
    }
}

@namespace Lumeo
@using System.ComponentModel
@using System.Globalization
@using Lumeo.GanttV3
@attribute [EditorBrowsable(EditorBrowsableState.Never)]

@* GanttBar — v3's single task-bar renderer (design spec Phase 2, T2 "read-only
   markup"). Renders EITHER a duration bar (background + progress fill) or,
   for Task.IsMilestone, a diamond (a rotated square — port of gantt-v2.js's
   SVG polygon geometry, gantt-v2.js lines 459-484: a square of side BarHeight
   rotated 45deg is exactly the same shape as v2's 4-point diamond polygon).
   Positioning is entirely via the --lumeo-gantt-bar-* CSS custom properties
   set on the absolutely positioned Tooltip wrapper (the wrapper carries the
   position/size so the AsChild inner div can stay a plain flex box) — the
   caller (GanttTimeline) computes X/Width/RowIndex from GanttScale and hands
   them in; this component has no knowledge of dates, view modes, or the
   scale table itself.

   NOTE (accessibility): the task spec asked for this component to be
   `internal`. The Razor compiler unconditionally generates a component's
   class as `public partial class` — there is no supported directive to make
   it `internal` (open feature requests: dotnet/aspnetcore#5516,
   dotnet/razor#8715), so a code-behind `internal partial class` here would
   only produce CS0262 (conflicting partial-declaration accessibility). This
   component is therefore `public` and its new members are recorded in
   PublicAPI.Unshipped.txt like any other public addition — see the T2 report
   for the full rationale; flagged for the reviewer/team lead to confirm.
   [EditorBrowsable(Never)] keeps this working-name API out of consumer
   IntelliSense until the Phase-4 rename (fix-round follow-up). *@
<Tooltip Class="@WrapperClass" AdditionalAttributes="@WrapperAttributes">
    <TooltipTrigger AsChild>
        <ChildContentSlot Context="slot">
            <div class="@InnerClass" @attributes="slot.Attributes">
                @if (Task.IsMilestone)
                {
                    <div class="lumeo-gantt-v3-milestone h-full w-full rounded-sm" style="@ColorStyle"></div>
                    <span class="lumeo-gantt-v3-milestone-label absolute start-full top-1/2 ms-2 -translate-y-1/2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs font-medium text-foreground">@Task.Name</span>
                }
                else
                {
